commit_message:
Do not just return when calling legacy image build

The return statement was not allowing the client to return a useful
error code when the legacy build failed. This change allows it to
return something meaningful by letting the ImageBuildError bubble up.

Change-Id: I5e614fd08ca72769dd4986a8abe4ba64cca55da0
Closes-Bug: #1632753

commit_message:
Enable enforce_password_check

By setting ENFORCE_PASSWORD_CHECK to `True`, it displays an 'Admin
Password' field on the Change Password form to verify that it is indeed
the admin logged-in who wants to change the password.

Change-Id: Ib11bef93b6b0c74063052875fa361290bf1e92fd

commit_message:
Elimination duplication of lots of DVR tests

The L3DvrTestCaseMigration class was just inheriting
and subsequently running all of the tests in the
L3DvrTestCase class. It doesn't have a separate setup
or mixin from the parent class so it was just duplicating
all of the tests for no reason.

Create a "base" test class so the migration class
can just run a single test.

Change-Id: Idbe347fa26e64c600cf3056d16a99c4ad46a2586

commit_message:
Use export in ansible_ssh_env file

In order to be able to rerun quickstart.sh with only specific tags
(for example, to only run tempest on a deployed overcloud), we need
to actually export these variables rather than just set them in the
current session.

Change-Id: I3ad9b3ba9783a05e3e62a36da5c3787cba090557

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-11-15 10:31:20.000000000', 'files': ['swift/obj/replicator.py', 'test/unit/obj/test_ssync_sender.py', 'test/unit/obj/common.py', 'test/unit/obj/test_replicator.py', 'test/unit/obj/test_ssync.py'], 'message': "Use per policy diskfile manager in object replicator

Changes the object replicator to get a DiskFileManager via the
DiskFileRouter class so that DiskFileManager instances are policy
specific. Currently the same replication policy DiskFileManager class
is always used, but this change future proofs the replicator for
possible other DiskFileManager implementations.

The change also gives the ObjectReplicator a _df_router variable,
making it consistent with the ObjectReconstructor, and allowing a
common way for ssync.Sender to access DiskFileManager instances via
it's daemon's _df_router instance, which is needed by [1].

Also, remove the use of FakeReplicator from the ssync test suite. It
was not necessary and risked masking divergence between ssync and the

[1] Related-Change: Ic7a4c932b59158d21a5fb4de9ed3ed57f249d068

Change-Id: I5176621729b7b75408723a246d45d4f5834f7309
"}]
commit_message:
Use per policy diskfile manager in object replicator

Changes the object replicator to get a DiskFileManager via the
DiskFileRouter class so that DiskFileManager instances are policy
specific. Currently the same replication policy DiskFileManager class
is always used, but this change future proofs the replicator for
possible other DiskFileManager implementations.

The change also gives the ObjectReplicator a _df_router variable,
making it consistent with the ObjectReconstructor, and allowing a
common way for ssync.Sender to access DiskFileManager instances via
it's daemon's _df_router instance, which is needed by [1].

Also, remove the use of FakeReplicator from the ssync test suite. It
was not necessary and risked masking divergence between ssync and the
replicator and reconstructor daemon implementations, which was
observed during review of [1].

[1] Related-Change: Ic7a4c932b59158d21a5fb4de9ed3ed57f249d068

Change-Id: I5176621729b7b75408723a246d45d4f5834f7309

commit_message:
support pandas.to_timedelta

pandas supports batch processing timedeltas. we should use that
instead of parsing each item individually.

testing showed it took 0.009s vs 0.026s to convert 1000 timestamps
using pandas vs current implementation respectively.

commit_message:
Use -y on zypper remove to avoid hanging

When using zypper remove, include the -y option to avoid stack.sh from
hanging waiting for user confirmation.  Due to output buffering, the
script could hang before giving the user the prompt to enter Y to
continue, making it unclear why the script was hanging.

Change-Id: I5ea761e5ae0829439953c385f8e7d0546acba886
Closes-Bug: 1642736

commit_message:
Log a warning when starting nova-net in non-cellsv1 deployments

We're going to make nova-network fail to start except in cellsv1
deployments before we release Ocata, so log a warning when starting
the service outside of cellsv1. The current plan is to make this
fatal after the o-2 milestone, essentially redoing commit
c07046edeee562142c90aa3cadd4bdc47b0a15da.

subject: Decouple deployment plans from Heat stacks
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-09-04 02:38:43.000000000', 'files': ['workbooks/deployment.yaml', 'tripleo_common/actions/deployment.py', 'tripleo_common/tests/actions/test_plan.py', 'tripleo_common/actions/templates.py', 'tripleo_common/actions/plan.py'], 'message': "Decouple deployment plans from Heat stacks

The actions and workflows for deploying a stack or deleting a
plan assume that a single plan is associated with a single
stack name. This doesn't allow an operator to create multiple
plans and deploy a stack from a selected plan with a different
name. e.g. operator creates and overcloud plan and
overcloud-test plan. The user should be able to chose either
plan to deploy a stack named 'overcloud'.

This patch removes the constraint from the plan deletion so any
plan with the same name as a stack can be deleted.  This patch
also adds a stack_name parameter to the deployment workflow and
associated actions.  The stack_name is defaulted to the plan name
for backwards compatiblility.

Change-Id: I6b0af5237d1a5ff886a96a320222c944f5301127
Closes-Bug: #1609454
"}]
commit_message:
Decouple deployment plans from Heat stacks

The actions and workflows for deploying a stack or deleting a
plan assume that a single plan is associated with a single
stack name. This doesn't allow an operator to create multiple
plans and deploy a stack from a selected plan with a different
name. e.g. operator creates and overcloud plan and
overcloud-test plan. The user should be able to chose either
plan to deploy a stack named 'overcloud'.

This patch removes the constraint from the plan deletion so any
plan with the same name as a stack can be deleted.  This patch
also adds a stack_name parameter to the deployment workflow and
associated actions.  The stack_name is defaulted to the plan name
for backwards compatiblility.

Change-Id: I6b0af5237d1a5ff886a96a320222c944f5301127
Closes-Bug: #1609454

subject: ec2 collector attempt config-drive before metadata server
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 360, 'name': 'Dan Prince', 'email': 'dprince@redhat.com', 'username': 'dan-prince'}, {'_account_id': 4328, 'name': 'Steven Hardy', 'email': 'steven.hardy@suse.com', 'username': 'shardy'}, {'_account_id': 4571, 'name': 'Steve Baker', 'email': 'sbaker@redhat.com', 'username': 'steve-stevebaker'}, {'_account_id': 6928, 'name': 'Ben Nemec', 'email': 'openstack@nemebean.com', 'username': 'bnemec'}, {'_account_id': 7144, 'name': 'James Slagle', 'email': 'jslagle@redhat.com', 'username': 'slagle'}, {'_account_id': 10873, 'name': 'Juan Antonio Osorio Robles', 'email': 'jaosorior@redhat.com', 'username': 'ejuaoso'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2016-10-12 20:39:19.000000000', 'files': ['os_collect_config/config_drive.py', 'os_collect_config/tests/test_collect.py', 'os_collect_config/ec2.py', 'os_collect_config/tests/test_config_drive.py', 'os_collect_config/tests/test_ec2.py'], 'message': 'ec2 collector attempt config-drive before metadata server

This change will first attempt to get ec2 metadata from a v2 config
drive before falling back to the nova metadata server if no config
drive is detected.

Config drive is enabled in overcloud nodes, so using this for
os-collect-config will allow the undercloud nova metadata server to be
disabled.

V2 of the config-drive was released in OpenStack Folsom, so a decision
was made to not support V1 discovery at all. This makes the block

commit_message:
ec2 collector attempt config-drive before metadata server

This change will first attempt to get ec2 metadata from a v2 config
drive before falling back to the nova metadata server if no config
drive is detected.

Config drive is enabled in overcloud nodes, so using this for
os-collect-config will allow the undercloud nova metadata server to be
disabled.

V2 of the config-drive was released in OpenStack Folsom, so a decision
was made to not support V1 discovery at all. This makes the block
device candidate selection much simpler than the cloud-init one[1].

[1] https://git.launchpad.net/cloud-init/tree/cloudinit/sources/DataSourceConfigDrive.py#n219

Change-Id: I2aec0544fe40c2e901aee38c79bb838a627d20da
Closes-Bug: #1619074

commit_message:
Ensure heat-domain hiera is in nodes that contain keystone

The commit that this depends on only works if heat is deployed in the
same node as keystone. Once we deploy them in different nodes, keystone
won't be able to retrieve the appropriate hieradata. This fixes that by
setting the appropriate hieradata to be deployed on the keystone service
by the heat profiles.

Related-Bug: #1642961
Change-Id: I1f08db68a14486526879d1a5a1ff78cb17686924
Depends-On: I7d42d04ef0c53dc1e62d684d8edacfed9fd28fbe

commit_message:
Pass the plan name when tagging nodes

Right now, tagging a node also updates the number of nodes assigned to
that role. However because the plan/container name wasn't being passed,
only the Mistral environment for the default 'overcloud' plan would
ever be updated with these new values, sometimes mistakenly.

Change-Id: Ifaeb9df96dbd7ca6a5553ecdc22c6ab8c56b7365
Partial-Bug: #1642342

Currently the x509 certificate setup is done after all the
openstack services have been deployed. This is OK because
none of the services require that the x509 certs exist
when they are being deployed. With the integration of TLS
into the nova novnc proxy (and later spice & serial proxy)
service, x509 certs will need to exist before Nova is
deployed.

The CA setup must thus be moved earlier in the devstack
deployment flow, prior to the setup of any services. One
part of the CA setup, however, fixes up the global cert
bundle locations and this can only be done after the
python requests module is install, thus must remain in
its current location.

Change-Id: Idcd264fb73bb88dc2f4280c53c013dfe4364afff
'}]
commit_message:
Move certificate setup earlier in deployment

Currently the x509 certificate setup is done after all the
openstack services have been deployed. This is OK because
none of the services require that the x509 certs exist
when they are being deployed. With the integration of TLS
into the nova novnc proxy (and later spice & serial proxy)
service, x509 certs will need to exist before Nova is
deployed.

The CA setup must thus be moved earlier in the devstack
deployment flow, prior to the setup of any services. One
part of the CA setup, however, fixes up the global cert
bundle locations and this can only be done after the
python requests module is install, thus must remain in
its current location.

Change-Id: Idcd264fb73bb88dc2f4280c53c013dfe4364afff

commit_message:
Store local network id to nb db

Currently, the local network id is stored in the df controller cache. Everytime df
controller restarts, the local network id will be re-generated. local network id
is used as the network identifier in OpenFlow(the metadata field). If it changes
after df controller restart, there might be duplicated flows, for example [1].

This patch stores the local network id as unique key in df nb db. So that, even if
df controller restarts, the local network id of network will not change.

[1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/586501/

Change-Id: Iaea5a95a996c4b4b90fffcf89c8a9dd2eaaa46a1
Partial-Bug: #1633082

commit_message:
devstack: make cni paths configurable

With this patch, we'll be able to place our cni executables in:

    /opt/stack/cni/bin

It also allows you to put configuration files for the kuryr cni driver
in:

    /opt/stack/cni/conf

For now we are not setting any non standard conf. It is foreseeable
though that some configuration like which host device to base the
ipvlan/vlan/macvlan devices off on container-in-vm environments could go
here (Although it could also be in a kuryr.conf for the cni driver).

Change-Id: I9abc0878612b97795c68c8d773e7a29e891d1a6f
Signed-off-by: Antoni S. Puimedon <asegurap@redhat.com>

Update host node 'dependents' when create/delete container node

This patch adds container node id to 'dependents' property of vm node,
and removes the id when container node is deleted.
The dependency update between cluster and container node will be done
in another patch.

compute.node.cpu.percent in workload_stabilization.

revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2016-10-18 21:28:11.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_utils/tests/test_strutils.py', 'oslo_utils/strutils.py'], 'message': "mask_password should check endswith key

oslo_utils.strutils.mask_password() has been in some cases matching
only when the key is exact (e.g. token), and in other cases matching
when the checked string contains a key that ends with the checked-for
key (e.g. x-auth-token). This change ends this inconsistency by
matching strings that contain a key which ends with the checked-for
key in all cases, so that we don't miss things like the x-auth-token
example.

It also cleans up the regular expressions for easier readability.

Change-Id: I437bc09bd332066ea916f0c600c6c4343ab2071f
"}]
commit_message:
mask_password should check endswith key

oslo_utils.strutils.mask_password() has been in some cases matching
only when the key is exact (e.g. token), and in other cases matching
when the checked string contains a key that ends with the checked-for
key (e.g. x-auth-token). This change ends this inconsistency by
matching strings that contain a key which ends with the checked-for
key in all cases, so that we don't miss things like the x-auth-token
example.

It also cleans up the regular expressions for easier readability.

Change-Id: I437bc09bd332066ea916f0c600c6c4343ab2071f

[{'number': 29, 'created': '2016-10-17 14:34:18.000000000', 'files': ['keystoneauth1/tests/unit/loading/test_v3.py', 'keystoneauth1/loading/_plugins/identity/v3.py', 'keystoneauth1/exceptions/oidc.py', 'releasenotes/notes/bug-1583961-8c140a10d97634a7.yaml', 'keystoneauth1/identity/v3/oidc.py', 'keystoneauth1/tests/unit/identity/test_identity_v3_oidc.py'], 'message': 'oidc: fix OpenID Connect authorization code grant_type

The current code is not working appropriately, as the authorization code
is a short-lived (the specification recommends less than 10 minutes) and
single use code, so it cannot be reused (if reused, the specification
states that all tokens obtained with the original code should be
revoked). Therefore, if we are implementing the authorization code grant
type we should follow the complete flow, that is:

1. obtain an authz code from the authz endpoint.
2. exchange the authz code with the token endpoint to get an access
   token.
3. exchange the access token with keystone to obtain an keystone token.

However (1) requires that the user authenticates with the IdP, and
According to the OAUTH 2.0 specification [1]:

    The authorization code grant type is used to obtain both access
    tokens and refresh tokens and is optimized for confidential clients.
    Since this is a redirection-based flow, the client must be capable
    of interacting with the resource owner’s user-agent (typically a web
    browser) and capable of receiving incoming requests (via
    redirection) from the authorization server.

[1] https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6749#section-4.1

So interacting with the user browser is expected. If it is not possible
to interact with the client in this way, then a different grant type
(like client_credentials (to be implemented)) should be used if
supported by the server.

In short, whenever we execute this authentication we need to fire up a
user-agent (browser) and we need to spawn a temporary local http server
where the request will be redirected so that we can get the returned
authorization code. Then, we can continue with the flow (i.e. obtaining
the access token and exchanging it with Keystone for a Keystone token).

Incidentally, the OpenID plugin does not accept the redirect_uri
argument anymore, as this is something internally managed by us, and
that the user should not provide.

Note that with the code as it is, the access token is not persisted, so
whenever the session ends it is lost. If a user makes 100 different
requests this implies that 100 browser windows or tabs will be opened.
A possible improvement for all OpenID Connect plugins is the persistence
of the access token so that it can be reused, and the implementation of
refresh tokens, instead of requiring authentication each time.

Closes-Bug: #1496258
Change-Id: I154b1d4a45a8a8272f286895afa1c14ff7044cf4
'}]
commit_message:
oidc: fix OpenID Connect authorization code grant_type

The current code is not working appropriately, as the authorization code
is a short-lived (the specification recommends less than 10 minutes) and
single use code, so it cannot be reused (if reused, the specification
states that all tokens obtained with the original code should be
revoked). Therefore, if we are implementing the authorization code grant
type we should follow the complete flow, that is:

1. obtain an authz code from the authz endpoint.
2. exchange the authz code with the token endpoint to get an access
   token.
3. exchange the access token with keystone to obtain an keystone token.

However (1) requires that the user authenticates with the IdP, and
According to the OAUTH 2.0 specification [1]:

    The authorization code grant type is used to obtain both access
    tokens and refresh tokens and is optimized for confidential clients.
    Since this is a redirection-based flow, the client must be capable
    of interacting with the resource owner’s user-agent (typically a web
    browser) and capable of receiving incoming requests (via
    redirection) from the authorization server.

[1] https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6749#section-4.1

So interacting with the user browser is expected. If it is not possible
to interact with the client in this way, then a different grant type
(like client_credentials (to be implemented)) should be used if
supported by the server.

In short, whenever we execute this authentication we need to fire up a
user-agent (browser) and we need to spawn a temporary local http server
where the request will be redirected so that we can get the returned
authorization code. Then, we can continue with the flow (i.e. obtaining
the access token and exchanging it with Keystone for a Keystone token).

Incidentally, the OpenID plugin does not accept the redirect_uri
argument anymore, as this is something internally managed by us, and
that the user should not provide.

Note that with the code as it is, the access token is not persisted, so
whenever the session ends it is lost. If a user makes 100 different
requests this implies that 100 browser windows or tabs will be opened.
A possible improvement for all OpenID Connect plugins is the persistence
of the access token so that it can be reused, and the implementation of
refresh tokens, instead of requiring authentication each time.

Closes-Bug: #1583961
Closes-Bug: #1496258
Change-Id: I154b1d4a45a8a8272f286895afa1c14ff7044cf4

commit_message:
mask_password should ignore case

oslo_utils.strutils.mask_password() has been doing case-sensitive
matching, which could easily cause us to miss masking something that
happens to use a different case. This switches to case-insensitive
matching.

Change-Id: I35cb98877a030f2eafe5b5ff88374c5a568bd53c

commit_message:
Yaql Tasks Function

This new function will allow user to get a list of tasks matching certain
filter. For example only task in state ERROR from the current execution.

This will work in both YAQL an Jinja2 expressions.

blueprint yaql-tasks-function

Change-Id: I218ad84770e93a25708ff64ce17e10f08187c6d3

Add upgading of mcollective agent while upgrading cluster

Upgrade using graph requires new nailgun agents because old one
is not compatible with 9.x graph-based engine. This patch contains
step described in upgrade runbook rewritten for removing bash magic.

commit_message:
Increase timeout for interfaces screen loading

Interfaces screen API was changed and a new API call was added
to fetch bond default attributes.
So, test time available for interfaces screen loading is increased
to make the test more stable.

Implements blueprint nics-and-nodes-attributes-via-plugin

Change-Id: I7190be21d7f232ed34631ea5682778dec2cf59cf

commit_message:
Remove unused bits from node management code in utils/node.py

* Removed set_nodes_state and wait_for_provision_state functions
  as this code was moved to workflows
* Removed "provide", "keystone_client" and "blocking" arguments and
  default value for "client" argument from register_all_nodes.
* Removed "blocking" argument and default value for "client" argument
  from register_ironic_node.

Related-Bug: #1637310

commit_message:
Remove DEVSTACK_GATE_TIMEOUT setting

We do not need to set this variable anymore, remove a stray version of
it. This was introduced as part of
I4e01e39d3113547002fffc094e38f1f395b16818 and not updated when we
remove DEVSTACK_GATE_TIMEOUT everywhere.

commit_message:
Replace deprecated "nova secgroup-*-rule" commands

The "nova secgroup-*-rule" commands are deprecated, so I replaced
them by the new "openstack security group rule" commands.
Also adjusted some lines that where too long.

In some places the replacement was already made, but with
deprecated options "--src-ip" and "--src-group" instead of "--remote-ip"
and "--remote-group". I also fixed that.

Change-Id: Ibfacc09f8301de567719c3b9db05821a006b7108
Closes-Bug: 1641636
Implements: blueprint use-openstack-command

commit_message:
Add generic reset-status method in admin actions' testcases

Replace '_issue_volume\backup\snapshot_reset' methods' arthimetic
with '_issue_resource_reset' to make code clean.

Also, make it convenient for subsequent reset operations on
other resources such as general group and their snapshots.

commit_message:
Make fernet the default token provider

Fernet tokens have been the default provider for keystone for some time
and we deprecated them in Newton. This change switches to use fernet
tokens as the default for the keystone class.

Change-Id: I15504f694c0ce5d35907585a8d5d61893cfe95ee

subject: [8.0] Add a reboot procedure for updates
revisions:
[{'number': 13, 'created': '2016-11-18 22:33:11.000000000', 'files': ['fuelweb_test/models/environment.py'], 'message': '[8.0] Add a reboot procedure for updates

Since sometimes we update kernels and system libraries for a master node
we have to reboot it after an update in order changes to take effect.
This
commit adds simplified mechanics for rebooting of the master node.
Also refactored the order of actions in packages updates, as it is
better to run an update having containers destroyed; removed the call to
"sync deployment tasks" as it is already contained in the fuel-library
package.
Added PEP8 conformance.

Change-Id: I9ad9201e0010763f1668ef04e8732ece69e9dc71
'}]
commit_message:
[8.0] Add a reboot procedure for updates

Since sometimes we update kernels and system libraries for a master node
we have to reboot it after an update in order changes to take effect.
This
commit adds simplified mechanics for rebooting of the master node.
Also refactored the order of actions in packages updates, as it is
better to run an update having containers destroyed; removed the call to
"sync deployment tasks" as it is already contained in the fuel-library
package.
Added PEP8 conformance.

Change-Id: I9ad9201e0010763f1668ef04e8732ece69e9dc71

commit_message:
[PY3] byte/string conversions and enable PY3 test

* The dict.items()[0] will raise a TypeError in PY3,
  as dict.items() doesn't return a list any more in PY3
  but a view of list.
* Webob response body should be bytes not strings so used
  oslo_utils.encodeutils.safe_decode to decode it.

Partially implements blueprint: goal-python35
Co-Authored-By: ChangBo Guo(gcb) <eric.guo@easystack.cn>

Change-Id: I38d416923bc0cec0ca98c4494dd1e06cd49671cf

commit_message:
New project proposal: python-redfish

The DMTF has published a new specification called Redfish (refer to
http://www.dmtf.org/standards/redfish) to provide a RESTful based API to manage
servers in a standard way. This project provides a client and a library to
interact with Redfish based systems, and is used to develop the Ironic Redfish
driver.

Change-Id: Icef9d1e93ea3c443c52a409079a7e7e37f9c797f

commit_message:
Have cluster-show list all ips

When you do a cluster-show, the instance list contains all ips.
The summary (which is the one displayed and used for tests)
only lists the first ip from each instance. It should list them
all, so the user could potentially chose which one they wanted
(i.e. an IPV4 address vs. an IPV6 one).

Depends-On: I54edc4acac09ca2278f525c08ad0d87576f0549e

Closes-Bug: 1642695

subject: Fail on deleting non-existing database
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-11-16 20:10:12.000000000', 'files': ['trove/guestagent/datastore/mysql_common/service.py', 'trove/extensions/mysql/models.py', 'trove/tests/scenario/runners/database_actions_runners.py', 'trove/extensions/mysql/service.py'], 'message': 'Fail on deleting non-existing database

Check that the database exists before deleting it and
fail if it does not.

Trove database API implementation closely followed MySQL
behavior which is to silently ignore deletes on non-existing
databases.
This strategy however no longer works that well with
other datastores which generally fail.

Trove users should be given a consistent experience.
Failing with an explanatory message is safer with respect to other
datastores and it is also consistent with how other Trove API
(user, backup, cluster) work.

Note: guestagent implementation was fix to handle
      limit=None in database (and user) queries.
      N >= None always returns True

Change-Id: I1dc26c7b40d6e4867b145b8470e6e5277e5dcdb4
Closes-Bug: 1293954
'}]
commit_message:
Fail on deleting non-existing database

Check that the database exists before deleting it and
fail if it does not.

Trove database API implementation closely followed MySQL
behavior which is to silently ignore deletes on non-existing
databases.
This strategy however no longer works that well with
other datastores which generally fail.

Trove users should be given a consistent experience.
Failing with an explanatory message is safer with respect to other
datastores and it is also consistent with how other Trove API
(user, backup, cluster) work.

Note: guestagent implementation was fix to handle
      limit=None in database (and user) queries.
      N >= None always returns True

Change-Id: I1dc26c7b40d6e4867b145b8470e6e5277e5dcdb4
Closes-Bug: 1293954

commit_message:
Fix the singleton pattern in operation engine

The 'OperationManager' and 'UserTrustManager' does not use the
real singleton pattern. Although, the instances of them will be
the same one, the member variables of instance will be reset.
Because '__init__' will be invoked each time creating a new
instance.

Change-Id: I96d11491c33709724ffaf903a55f783cd0fc44a3

Those deleted kernel parameters are extremely heavy debug.

complicate motherboard and lots of pci devices(Lenovo RD640).

commit_message:
Delete kernel debug related parameter for performance

Those deleted kernel parameters are extremely heavy debug.
The boot process is rather slow on machines which has a
complicate motherboard and lots of pci devices(Lenovo RD640).
The debug process costs so much resouce, evetually it will impact
normal functions, such as cpus are so busy dealing with debug
info in kernelspace, they do not have time to reponse udev
event in userspace and failed to bring up pci devices.

Change-Id: I964c5fbc7f5b7d0ba6d1dd0166db3e4234179afa
Closes-bug: #1632592

commit_message:
Set SUBNETPOOL_PREFIX_V4 to match FIXED_RANGE

With [1] devstack started to setup subnetpools instead of just using
FIXED_RANGE. Set the SUBNET* parameters accordingly, so that the
same private network is being created in the gate jobs as before.

Note that we need to allow at least four subnets in the pool, otherwise
tempest.api.compute.admin.test_auto_allocate_network
 .AutoAllocateNetworkTest.test_server_multi_create_auto_allocate
will fail.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/356026

Partial-Bug: 1629133
Change-Id: I8f3d0d2a77999fc15ba10044930b37c030ad63dd

[{'number': 4, 'created': '2016-11-07 10:23:29.000000000', 'files': ['lib/neutron_plugins/services/l3'], 'message': 'Change default IPv6 subnetpool prefix

Using the documentation prefix as real world default for IPv6 is
bad, instead use a random prefix from fd00::/8 just as for
FIXED_RANGE_V6.

We have a /48 as random prefix in total, we use a /64 from it for
FIXED_RANGE_V6 and in order to avoid overlapping the subnet pool range
with that one, we use the next /56 after the one occupied by
FIXED_RANGE_V6. This will allow for the creation of 256 subnets out of
this pool.

Change-Id: Ied96ea4faff05c8f62dbb1ec46a6903d672c71d8
'}]
commit_message:
Change default IPv6 subnetpool prefix

Using the documentation prefix as real world default for IPv6 is
bad, instead use a random prefix from fd00::/8 just as for
FIXED_RANGE_V6.

We have a /48 as random prefix in total, we use a /64 from it for
FIXED_RANGE_V6 and in order to avoid overlapping the subnet pool range
with that one, we use the next /56 after the one occupied by
FIXED_RANGE_V6. This will allow for the creation of 256 subnets out of
this pool.

Change-Id: Ied96ea4faff05c8f62dbb1ec46a6903d672c71d8

commit_message:
Disable cloud-init network auto configuration

The previos implementation doesn't fix the problem. Cloud-init
creates /etc/network/interfaces.d/50-cloud-init.cfg which prevents
to set static IP.

commit_message:
Process stats from ElasticSearch matched by IP

In some scenarios ElasticSearch returns its IP address
as 'host' value. This was filtered out when looking for
matching hostname. This commit adds IP address to
allowed 'hostnames'

Change-Id: I3fd1adf291c2eead0c8c601140a5e4b1487ba9a4
(cherry picked from commit 7f7588d10f064535c0bb0f8dbc5126fe2ad23aaa)

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-18 11:48:31.000000000', 'files': ['puppet/services/pacemaker/haproxy.yaml', 'environments/puppet-pacemaker.yaml'], 'message': 'Disable keepalived for HA deployments via t-h-t

Currently this is disabled via a conditional in the keepalived
profile in puppet-tripleo, but this will be incompatible with
the planned composable upgrades implementation.  Instead we should
disable the service template by mapping to OS::Heat::None, and
ensure the haproxy manifest uses the t-h-t generated hiera value
keepalived_enabled instead of hard-coding a hiera override in the
haproxy template.

Change-Id: I85a8b1cca7268506de22adfb3a8ce7faa4f157ef
Partial-Bug: #1642936
Depends-On: I90faf51881bd05920067c1e1d82baf5d7586af23
'}]
commit_message:
Disable keepalived for HA deployments via t-h-t

Currently this is disabled via a conditional in the keepalived
profile in puppet-tripleo, but this will be incompatible with
the planned composable upgrades implementation.  Instead we should
disable the service template by mapping to OS::Heat::None, and
ensure the haproxy manifest uses the t-h-t generated hiera value
keepalived_enabled instead of hard-coding a hiera override in the
haproxy template.

Change-Id: I85a8b1cca7268506de22adfb3a8ce7faa4f157ef
Partial-Bug: #1642936
Depends-On: I90faf51881bd05920067c1e1d82baf5d7586af23

commit_message:
Remove network-gateway element from image build

that configuration mechanism (and hasn't for quite some time), as it
uses os-net-config to configure networking settings instead.

Change-Id: If88452c526833d3fd115e6f9680d98f5c6513c63

commit_message:
HyperV: use os-brick for volume related operations

This patch refactors volumeops.py to use os-brick for volume
related operations.

The immediate benefits are:
* FC support
* improved iSCSI MPIO support
* simplified volume connect/disconnect workflow

Change-Id: Ib21947141aadca1fa6cb99afc07a175ce14d192e
Depends-On: I19dfc8dd2e9e8a1b17675b55c63de903804480e4
Implements: blueprint hyperv-use-os-brick

commit_message:
No longer specify announce list in tag message

Announce list used to be passed from the release YAML to
the announcement script using meta information in the tag.
Since we now enforce all announcements to go to the same
list, stop passing that information around.

Change-Id: I37f24fe4a716c9b64f241d7a45da8e8bce8b55c2
Depends-On: I604288d266cbe53ee4d9b8567331f94c3c684088

When the release announces were posted on the general -announce
list, subject lines contained "[new]" and "release" keywords to

commit_message:
Remove redundant information from subject

When the release announces were posted on the general -announce
list, subject lines contained "[new]" and "release" keywords to
make it clear what the announce was about. Now that they are
posted to a specific list, this information is redundant and
wastes precious space.

Change-Id: Iee60c7f0d7c87de4bafdcce90ff5aa25b60fe649

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-11-17 06:20:22.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py'], 'message': "Fix mock arg list order in test_driver.py

When we use nest patch decorators the mocks, they are passed in to the
decorated function in the same order they applied, this means should be
from the bottom up. Though We have never use these arguments in this
function and the order may not very important, it's a little misleading.
So I think we should fix it.

Change-Id: I459780a17998382b61f56377bfa17651a5f99f51

commit_message:
Fix mock arg list order in test_driver.py

When we use nest patch decorators the mocks, they are passed in to the
decorated function in the same order they applied, this means should be
from the bottom up. Though We have never use these arguments in this
function and the order may not very important, it's a little misleading.
So I think we should fix it.

Change-Id: I459780a17998382b61f56377bfa17651a5f99f51

commit_message:
Add support for 'zun run' command at server side

This patch adds support for 'zun run' command at
server side, for implementing this 'run' method is
implemented in container controller. REST api endpoint
to access this method would be '/v1/containers/run'.

Fix failure of systemd service kube-ui

The systemd service kube-ui failed because it does not
know the HOME environment variable.
Also updated script to handle already existing namespace,
rc and service.

Similar issue from upstream is as follows:

subject: Remove py27 job from Horizon
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-07 12:49:47.000000000', 'files': ['zuul/layout.yaml'], 'message': 'Remove py27 job from Horizon

Horizon runs py27 with multiple versions of django as py27dj{18,19,110}.
The py27 job will always use whichever version of django is in
upper-constraints; because of this, Horizon is effectively running one
of its py27 jobs twice at all times (currently py27 against Django 1.8.x)

Rather than have to keep altering the jobs every time there is a
requirements bump, we should just stick to the jobs that match the
appropriate django versions that Horizon currently supports.

Change-Id: I3073c2017c2776716119ad6783c3d99780bae6c0
'}]
commit_message:
Remove py27 job from Horizon

Horizon runs py27 with multiple versions of django as py27dj{18,19,110}.
The py27 job will always use whichever version of django is in
upper-constraints; because of this, Horizon is effectively running one
of its py27 jobs twice at all times (currently py27 against Django 1.8.x)

Rather than have to keep altering the jobs every time there is a
requirements bump, we should just stick to the jobs that match the
appropriate django versions that Horizon currently supports.

Change-Id: I3073c2017c2776716119ad6783c3d99780bae6c0

commit_message:
The translation of server's IP as output is error

In the template version of 2013-05-23, the intrinsic function of
get_attr doesn't support keys or indexes, it requires
2014-10-16 or higher, the syntax is below:
  get_attr:
    <resource name>
    <attribute name>
    <key/index 1> (optional) not support in 2013-05-23
    <key/index 2> (optional) not support in 2013-05-23
The translation about compute node's ip address only uses two
parameters currently.

So, updated the template version to 2014-10-16 in the code and
yaml template files.

This patch only resolves the ip output from [server, networks, private, 0]
(which is error) to [server, first_address], and the
complete solution for output according to tosca definition
please refer to patch:
"https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat-translator/+bug/1626079".

Co-Authored-By: shangxdy <shang.xiaodong@zte.com.cn>

Change-Id: I78492910280c977a64682b77c6fc4750b5690ca9
Closes-bug: #1621923

commit_message:
Ensure heat-domain hiera is in nodes that contain keystone

The commit that this depends on only works if heat is deployed in the
same node as keystone. Once we deploy them in different nodes, keystone
won't be able to retrieve the appropriate hieradata. This fixes that by
setting the appropriate hieradata to be deployed on the keystone service
by the heat profiles.

Change-Id: I1f08db68a14486526879d1a5a1ff78cb17686924
Depends-On: I7d42d04ef0c53dc1e62d684d8edacfed9fd28fbe

commit_message:
Sync tools/tox_install.sh

Sync tools/tox_install.sh with python-openstackclient. This brings in
the following improvements:

* Do not leave temporary directory around, instead delete temporary
  directory directly after usage (change
  I939eae82dba3287fd4e4086128ebf4609a0e0770).
* Do not set ZUUL_BRANCH explicitely and remove unused if condition
  (change I0077c986a17d6bb92791474e03d1e77776e9382f).

Change-Id: I7b408838a29f33c3747829ecd5f30c8dc967a592
(cherry picked from commit 09a7782403b74f9831ccca5d1c34a3f7fd7f6913)

subject: Add TODO item about referencing existing pool
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-17 09:23:39.000000000', 'files': ['TODO.rst'], 'message': "Add TODO item about referencing existing pool

There are use cases where a user has created a pool of volumes, or a
pool of ports, or a pool of floating IPs before he/she creates a VM
cluster. When creating nodes for the cluster, he/she wants to reference
a resource from the said pool. This doesn't have to go to heat stack
profile. We are adding this to the queue so that someone in future can
pick it up.

Change-Id: I79f29c48fbe9bde1fff1d08dce9045d6e59ad6dc
"}]
commit_message:
Add TODO item about referencing existing pool

There are use cases where a user has created a pool of volumes, or a
pool of ports, or a pool of floating IPs before he/she creates a VM
cluster. When creating nodes for the cluster, he/she wants to reference
a resource from the said pool. This doesn't have to go to heat stack
profile. We are adding this to the queue so that someone in future can
pick it up.

Change-Id: I79f29c48fbe9bde1fff1d08dce9045d6e59ad6dc

commit_message:
Remove join filter from pip module tasks

as a list, removing the need for us to implement the join
filter to optimise the install execution.

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-10-25 12:42:29.000000000', 'files': ['keystonemiddleware/auth_token/__init__.py'], 'message': "Print exception with log level of warning when fetching token failed

It is a better practice to print the exception with log level of warning
in 'fetch_token' when fetching token failed, as done in the method of
'_do_fetch_token'. Generally, the log level is set higher than 'debug' in
the production environment to avoid printing trivial logs.

Change-Id: Iba789d1986ab2f8209b72d9e01d75c4fa345eb39
"}]
commit_message:
Print exception with log level of warning when fetching token failed

It is a better practice to print the exception with log level of warning
in 'fetch_token' when fetching token failed, as done in the method of
'_do_fetch_token'. Generally, the log level is set higher than 'debug' in
the production environment to avoid printing trivial logs.

Change-Id: Iba789d1986ab2f8209b72d9e01d75c4fa345eb39

commit_message:
POC for neutron rootwrap daemon with XenServer

This patchset aims to implement rootwrap deamon mode when hypervisor is
XenServer. The main idea is to reuse the existing functionality provided
by oslo.rootwrap. Currently, subclassing and overriding classes/functions
from oslo.rootwrap to make the mechanism of XenServer rootwrap daemon the
same way compared with current neutron rootwrap daemon. This patchset is
also compatible with current none rootwrap daemon mode when XenServer is
used as hypervisor

Related-bug: 1585510

Change-Id: Ic5c40473256570b452fb2a2eaa1e457f6866dccc

commit_message:
scale out or delete instance based on workload

The workload of VM is an important feature concerning user experience.
Users may experience delay when the instance has a heavy workload.
On the contrary, when workload is not that heavy and most of the
instances remain Idle, this may cause waste of resources.

Currently,the work of adjusting instances according to the workload of
VM are done by users themselves manually where they found VM are
overloaded or underloaded.

In this bp,watcher can metric the workload of instance and deal with
this problem automatically for users when it finds the workload of
a VM is not reasonable.

Change-Id: I840f723066477d01002c92bde52f389fc50f96b3

commit_message:
Fix runtime ssh host keys script

The script is set -e and set -o pipefail, unfortauntely this intersects
with `yes n`'s non zero exit code behavior when it receives an interrupt
like sigpipe. As a result stop setting pipefail so that we treat those
errors as "normal" and only fail if ssh-keygen fails.

Change-Id: I5447df97c9888cae3007e235e2fea44df61af28e

commit_message:
Avoid infinite loop while placing parts

Previously, we could over-assign how many parts should be in a tier.
This would cause the local `parts` variable to go negative, which meant
that our `while parts` loop would never terminate.

Change-Id: Id7e7889742ca37cf1a9c0d55fba78d967e90e8d0
Closes-Bug: 1642538
(cherry picked from commit 2e7a7347fc58676fbaabce3d87a15866796d32e4)

subject: Set owner of drive-audit recon cache to swift user
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-18 11:22:13.000000000', 'files': ['swift/common/utils.py', 'bin/swift-drive-audit', 'etc/drive-audit.conf-sample', 'test/unit/common/test_utils.py', 'doc/source/admin_guide.rst'], 'message': 'Set owner of drive-audit recon cache to swift user

Fixies this problem:
* swift-drive-audit needs to be run by root, because only root have
  "umount" permission
* swift-object servers typically runs as user swift
* if swift-drive-audit is run by root, /var/cache/swift/drive.recon is
  owned by root, with 0o600
* recon middleware (inside swift-object-server) can't read this cache
  file: swift-object: Error reading recon cache file

This patch adds "user" option to drive-audit config file. Recon cache
is chowned to this user.
(cherry picked from commit 9847796)

Change-Id: Ibf20543ee690b7c5a37fabd1540fd5c0c7b638c9
'}]
commit_message:
Set owner of drive-audit recon cache to swift user

Fixies this problem:
* swift-drive-audit needs to be run by root, because only root have
  "umount" permission
* swift-object servers typically runs as user swift
* if swift-drive-audit is run by root, /var/cache/swift/drive.recon is
  owned by root, with 0o600
* recon middleware (inside swift-object-server) can't read this cache
  file: swift-object: Error reading recon cache file

This patch adds "user" option to drive-audit config file. Recon cache
is chowned to this user.
(cherry picked from commit 9847796)

Change-Id: Ibf20543ee690b7c5a37fabd1540fd5c0c7b638c9

[{'number': 8, 'created': '2016-11-16 20:41:06.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_db/sqlalchemy/test_base.py', 'oslo_db/sqlalchemy/test_fixtures.py', 'oslo_db/tests/sqlalchemy/test_fixtures.py'], 'message': 'Break optimize_db_test_loader into package and module level

This unittest-compatible load_tests function was not
well organized for package-level tests and was broken
for module-level usage; as in the case of module-level usage,
the "pattern" parameter was being passed, which was unexpected
since the Python 2.7 documentation for unittest claims it will
be None.  However, we are using subunit to run tests, which
uses the unittest2 library that achieves compatibility with
Python 3 - in Python 3, the documentation was changed here
to note that "pattern" may be present (and in fact it is).

Instead, break it into optimize_package_test_loader and
optimize_module_test_loader.  The former assumes placement
inside of __init__.py only and the latter assumes placement
inside of a specific module only.

The issue with this function was observed when trying to get
OptimisingTestSuite to work correctly with neutron; tests
would be duplicated due to the double-search.  In local testing
it was shown that the function could cause recursion overflows.

It has been observed that using this function at the module level
is of great use when running subsets of tests, since the package-level
load_tests function is not consulted unless the test run is package-wide.

Change-Id: I267fd2fbc16504c11addef870fc8d4fc500da7d9
'}]
commit_message:
Break optimize_db_test_loader into package and module level

This unittest-compatible load_tests function was not
well organized for package-level tests and was broken
for module-level usage; as in the case of module-level usage,
the "pattern" parameter was being passed, which was unexpected
since the Python 2.7 documentation for unittest claims it will
be None.  However, we are using subunit to run tests, which
uses the unittest2 library that achieves compatibility with
Python 3 - in Python 3, the documentation was changed here
to note that "pattern" may be present (and in fact it is).

Instead, break it into optimize_package_test_loader and
optimize_module_test_loader.  The former assumes placement
inside of __init__.py only and the latter assumes placement
inside of a specific module only.

The issue with this function was observed when trying to get
OptimisingTestSuite to work correctly with neutron; tests
would be duplicated due to the double-search.  In local testing
it was shown that the function could cause recursion overflows.

It has been observed that using this function at the module level
is of great use when running subsets of tests, since the package-level
load_tests function is not consulted unless the test run is package-wide.

Change-Id: I267fd2fbc16504c11addef870fc8d4fc500da7d9

[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-11-16 17:41:45.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_db/sqlalchemy/compat/utils.py', 'oslo_db/tests/sqlalchemy/test_exc_filters.py'], 'message': 'Adjust SAVEPOINT cause test for SQLA 1.1

commit_message:
Adjust SAVEPOINT cause test for SQLA 1.1

SQLAlchemy 1.1 has repaired some of the failure modes
for Session.rollback(), including the MySQL case where the savepoint
identifier gets lost, such that the Session is in a more usable
state than before.  A side effect of this is that the test
here in oslo.db only hits a single error handler, not two.

SQLAlchemy upstream is described at:

https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/latest/changelog/migration_11.html#improved-session-state-when-a-savepoint-is-cancelled-by-the-database

Change-Id: I324f288701e9ffd241de638e0e0419dc8d9c1264

commit_message:
Add experimental upgrade testing jobs for OpenStack-Ansible roles

This patch adds experimental upgrade testing jobs for the following
OpenStack-Ansible roles:

Cinder
Glance
Keystone
Neutron
Nova
Swift

There is a job for ubuntu-xenial and CentOS-7 for each role.
ubuntu-trusty will be removed in Ocata, so no upgrade gate is added
for Trusty.

Additionally, an integrated AIO upgrade build upgrade is added for the
integrated openstack-ansible repository.

The regex to skip upgrade jobs, for stable/newton and earlier, for
keystone has been ammended to include all repositories.

Change-Id: I4e4219e68dc0919bc59df41da75df374577d0034

subject: Devstack plugin to federate with testshib.org
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2016-11-17 18:54:53.000000000', 'files': ['devstack/lib/federation.sh', 'devstack/files/federation/shib_apache_alias.txt', 'devstack/plugin.sh', 'devstack/files/federation/shibboleth2.xml', 'devstack/files/federation/shib_apache_handler.txt'], 'message': 'Devstack plugin to federate with testshib.org

In a previous patch, I implemented a Devstack plugin to enable
federation and idp features in keystone. The plugin was to be
configured from environment variables for the idp entityID, metadata,
sp_auth_url, sp_url, etc. Providing an endless and untestable matrix
of combinations. Therefore the review was gathering dust waiting for
brave reviewers.

This review extracts the meat of the previous patch and removes all
the configuration options. This plugin now does one thing only: It
installs mod_shibboleth and sets up testshib.org as the IdP for keystone.

While testshib.org will not be used in our functional testing, this
is a necessary first step to make such complex changes more testable
reproducible and reviewable.

A follow-up patch will install a shibboleth-idp, and either that one,
or a later one, will switch from testshib.org to the local shibboleth.

This plugin will not yet be run as part of the gate, as "enable_service
federation" needs to be added to the Devstack options.

To run add the following after the lines that set up keystone from a
gerrit review:

enable_plugin keystone $KEYSTONE_REPO
enable_service keystone-saml2-federation

Change-Id: I6f7491ff063359d7065c77b00fe5bfc76f8587d6
'}]
commit_message:
Devstack plugin to federate with testshib.org

In a previous patch, I implemented a Devstack plugin to enable
federation and idp features in keystone. The plugin was to be
configured from environment variables for the idp entityID, metadata,
sp_auth_url, sp_url, etc. Providing an endless and untestable matrix
of combinations. Therefore the review was gathering dust waiting for
brave reviewers.

This review extracts the meat of the previous patch and removes all
the configuration options. This plugin now does one thing only: It
installs mod_shibboleth and sets up testshib.org as the IdP for keystone.

While testshib.org will not be used in our functional testing, this
is a necessary first step to make such complex changes more testable
reproducible and reviewable.

A follow-up patch will install a shibboleth-idp, and either that one,
or a later one, will switch from testshib.org to the local shibboleth.

This plugin will not yet be run as part of the gate, as "enable_service
federation" needs to be added to the Devstack options.

To run add the following after the lines that set up keystone from a
gerrit review:

enable_plugin keystone $KEYSTONE_REPO
enable_service keystone-saml2-federation

Change-Id: I6f7491ff063359d7065c77b00fe5bfc76f8587d6

v2.0 formatted tokens. This commit leaves a comment in the code
to remind us to remove that if branch when Pike opens for
development.

commit_message:
Remove metadata from token provider

The metadata stuff in the token provider was there as a v2-ism.
This commit removes it from the token provider and leaves it's bits
in the v2.0 token controller.

Change-Id: I4b37289c06df2012ed4473227df5c309440af162

commit_message:
Dispatched out network interface info to all hardware managers

This patch dispatches out the network_interface_info
to allow vendor hardware managers to plug the spacific
implementation. It also move neworking releated methods
form hardware to netutils
Related-Bug: #1532534

commit_message:
Restore worker configs for mitaka and below

When I made the change in I9d3ec8b698ca2ee985334f40ad8cd495c90db9b7
I don't think I realized the mitaka env didn't have its own copy of
the parameters.  The end result was that older releases aren't
getting the correct worker config.  This restores the parameters
just to the mitaka file.

commit_message:
Implements image_pull_policy

This patch implements image_pull_policy, which determines if
the image should be pulled prior to starting the container.

It can have following values:
ifnotpresent: only pull the image if it does not already exist on the node.
always: Always pull the image from repositery.
never: never pull the image

If image_pull_policy is not specified then:
1. If the tag is latest, defaults image_pull_policy is always.
2. Otherwise default is ifnotpresent

Partial-Implements: blueprint image-pull-policy
Change-Id: If2715d7724fd5336fb25d380f125e1485ca302d0

subject: Fix signal handling for daemons with InternalClient
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-18 11:23:54.000000000', 'files': ['test/probe/test_signals.py', 'swift/common/daemon.py', 'test/unit/common/test_daemon.py'], 'message': 'Fix signal handling for daemons with InternalClient

The intentional use of "bare except" handling in catch_errors and some
daemons to prevent propagation on unexpected errors that do not
inherit from Exception (like eventlet.Timeout) or even BaseException
(like old-style classes) has the side effect of spuriously "handling"
*expected* errors like when a signal handler raises SystemExit.

The signal handler installed in our Daemon is intended to ensure first
that the entire process group and any forked processes (like rsync's)
receive the SIGTERM signal and also that the process itself
terminates.

The use of sys.exit was not a concious grandiose plans for graceful
shutdown (like the running[0] = False trick that wsgi server parent
process do) - the desired behavior for SIGTERM is to stop - hard.

This change ensures the original goals and intentions of our signal
handler are fulfilled without the undesirable side effect that can
cause our daemons to confusingly log an expected message to stop as an
unexpected error, and start ignoring additional SIGTERM messages;
forcing our kind operators to resort to brutal process murder.

Closes-Bug: #1489209
Change-Id: I9d2886611f6db2498cd6a8f81a58f2a611f40905
(cherry picked from commit c2ce92a)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix signal handling for daemons with InternalClient

The intentional use of "bare except" handling in catch_errors and some
daemons to prevent propagation on unexpected errors that do not
inherit from Exception (like eventlet.Timeout) or even BaseException
(like old-style classes) has the side effect of spuriously "handling"
*expected* errors like when a signal handler raises SystemExit.

The signal handler installed in our Daemon is intended to ensure first
that the entire process group and any forked processes (like rsync's)
receive the SIGTERM signal and also that the process itself
terminates.

The use of sys.exit was not a concious grandiose plans for graceful
shutdown (like the running[0] = False trick that wsgi server parent
process do) - the desired behavior for SIGTERM is to stop - hard.

This change ensures the original goals and intentions of our signal
handler are fulfilled without the undesirable side effect that can
cause our daemons to confusingly log an expected message to stop as an
unexpected error, and start ignoring additional SIGTERM messages;
forcing our kind operators to resort to brutal process murder.

Closes-Bug: #1489209
Change-Id: I9d2886611f6db2498cd6a8f81a58f2a611f40905
(cherry picked from commit c2ce92a)

commit_message:
Compare the encoded tag more accurately for huawei driver

huawei driver uses a tag '!$$$' to indicate if username/password
is encoded or not in huawei configuration file.

Currently 'find' method is used to check if this tag is included
in the configuration string, but it'll misread if the tag is
included not in front of the string.

So change the comparing statement to a more accurate way, compare
the front slice of the string directly to the tag.

Change-Id: Ic343970578477362460340b01e5766e03c7d63a4
Closes-Bug: 1635073

commit_message:
Remove issue_v3_token in favor of issue_token

Since we don't have a reason to hold on to a version specific
token method name, we can rename it to be just issue_token.

Now the token provider interface has two intergral methods,
validate_token and issue_token. From a third-party perspective, this
makes it easier to maintain a proprietary token provider since it
eliminates a lot of version specific things from the provider
implementation. From a keystone perspective, we are isolating the
numerous token validation and issuance paths to a since route. This
will make understanding the code easier for other developers and
eventually easier to optimize.

Change-Id: I71a04b42e931338b8bd59e479636b6199c7c2d76

Depends-On: Ia51f28a70ae099f1ec93851d271db8556aced836

commit_message:
Remove issue_v2_token

In a previous commit we made all calls to issue_v2_token use
issue_v3_token instead. Any tokens that needed to be represented
as a v2.0 token we translate using the V2TokenDataHelper class.

At this point nothing really uses the issue_v2_token method and it
can be safely removed. A subsequent patch will rename the
issue_v3_token method to just issue_token since we no longer need
to make a distinction between two different methods.

Depends-On: Ia51f28a70ae099f1ec93851d271db8556aced836
Change-Id: I7d3b583cbec9a095ab8cc20c5d6c0a6127e37068

The token controller had quite a few case statements depending on
which type of authentication was required based on the format of the
authenticate request.

This commit uses the generator pattern to give the
token.controllers.Auth.authenticate() method the right authentication
object based on the format of the request. Each authentication method

commit_message:
refactor the token controller

The token controller had quite a few case statements depending on
which type of authentication was required based on the format of the
authenticate request.

This commit uses the generator pattern to give the
token.controllers.Auth.authenticate() method the right authentication
object based on the format of the request. Each authentication method
just implements an `authenticate()` method that returns a tuple of
information.

commit_message:
Use issue_v3_token instead of issue_v2_token

This is following the same pattern we applied to the token validation
path by collapsing the v3 and v2.0 paths together. Here we are going
to use issue_v3_token and translate the response to a v2.0 format.

This is going to allow us the ability to simplify the token provider
interface, remove duplicate logic, and isolate specific v2.0 and v3
token-isms into specific areas.

One of the existing test cases changes to assert an Unauthorized
exception when a trustee is disabled, instead of a Forbidden exception.
The switch is because the behavior is consistent with regular users
trying to authenticate with a token when their user is disabled (a 401
is expected). We're making that behavior consistent when a trustee is
disabled.

A subsequent patch will remove issue_v2_token entirely.

Change-Id: I191ce36b2f11f7353e2e3d601af1bda96987613b

commit_message:
Use tempest config to correctly set volume size

Volume size should be determined from tempest config.
In tempest, you can set what base volume size is as
CONF.volume.volume_size. This helps makes test pass
on environments where ScaleIO is cinder backend, and
in ScaleIO base volume is 8 instead of 1.

Change-Id: Ic7479c47940ba23c1d1e31e7aad86937b4d04fe6

commit_message:
Remove "in-process-" from swift func jobs

Shorten the alternate functional test job names for swift to bring
them under the max shebang length limit for shebangs in the
resulting tox virtualenv in our job workspaces. This will need to be
coordinated with a similar change to swift's tox.ini after the job
configuration is applied.

Change-Id: Icdcf76f7d52e4cce03378c88946c49d28e328547

commit_message:
Add VolumeAttachStatus Enum

This change adds a new enum and field, VolumeAttachStatus
and VolumeAttachStatusField, that will hold the constants for the
'attach_status' field of the VolumeAttachStatus object. This enum
and field are based on the base oslo.versionedobjects enum and field.
This also changes over the volume object to use the new field. Finally,
all uses of strings for comparison and assignment to this field are
changed over to use the constants defined within the enum.

Partial-Implements: bp cinder-object-fields
Change-Id: Ie727348daf425bd988425767f9dfb82da4c3baa8

subject: Fix log-generator-user-by-row test
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-18 17:27:17.000000000', 'files': ['trove/tests/scenario/runners/guest_log_runners.py'], 'message': "Fix log-generator-user-by-row test

The log_generator_user_by_row tests fail sometimes as there may
be data written into the user log while the test is ongoing.
This changes the state from 'Published' to 'Partial' and the
test fails.

The test has been changed to also accept 'Partial' as a valid state.

Change-Id: Iab530fe503336c83e9b948c2c008d371a8030a1e
Closes-Bug: 1643015
"}]
commit_message:
Fix log-generator-user-by-row test

The log_generator_user_by_row tests fail sometimes as there may
be data written into the user log while the test is ongoing.
This changes the state from 'Published' to 'Partial' and the
test fails.

The test has been changed to also accept 'Partial' as a valid state.

Change-Id: Iab530fe503336c83e9b948c2c008d371a8030a1e
Closes-Bug: 1643015

commit_message:

apache config templates from local tree. Else, it would

commit_message:
Disable cloud-init network auto configuration

The previos implementation doesn't fix the problem. Cloud-init
creates /etc/network/interfaces.d/50-cloud-init.cfg which prevents
to set static IP.

Change-Id: I49d09dd37403a843adfe34be156e5e265b0f3e08
Signed-off-by: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

subject: Revert "DHCP agent: don't directly connect different subnets"
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-09-20 10:34:39.000000000', 'files': ['networking_calico/agent/linux/dhcp.py'], 'message': 'Revert "DHCP agent: don't directly connect different subnets"

This reverts commit 623fc4b115de329722b31c1e2b92b055b0964163.

Following the DHCP agent rework so as _not_ to coalesce subnets from
different Neutron networks, we no longer need that commit; and since it
added quite a bit of mostly duplicated code (from Neutron to
networking-calico), it is better to remove it again.

Change-Id: I32d762f8fa46df579f9c18fcb547fbcbe08b5c69
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "DHCP agent: don't directly connect different subnets"

This reverts commit 623fc4b115de329722b31c1e2b92b055b0964163.

Following the DHCP agent rework so as _not_ to coalesce subnets from
different Neutron networks, we no longer need that commit; and since it
added quite a bit of mostly duplicated code (from Neutron to
networking-calico), it is better to remove it again.

Change-Id: I32d762f8fa46df579f9c18fcb547fbcbe08b5c69

commit_message:
Using assertIsNone() instead of assertEqual(None, ...)

Following OpenStack Style Guidelines[1]:
[H203] Unit test assertions tend to give better messages for more
specific assertions. As a result, assertIsNone(...) is preferred
over assertEqual(None, ...) and assertIs(None, ...)

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#unit-tests-and-assertraises

Change-Id: I31acdb6728dbf1c78826682248cac1c3c0e1c77a

commit_message:

messaging server, oslo.service.service for specifying graceful
shutdown timeout, oslo.db.concurrency for enabling thread pooling
for all DB API calls, oslo.config to configure config directory,
oslo.service.wsgi for wsgi config options and oslo.versionedobjects
for versioned objects related config options.

commit_message:
Remove oslo-incubator use in other client plugins

oslo incubator code is planned to be removed from the clients
this cycle. Remove the redundant usage of it from other client
plugins.

This also includes an unrelated change(to remove the vpnaas
post configuration, as we have removed the plugin from the
gate jobs), to fix the gate.

Last but not least, it limits the number of connections to the database
to work around a convergence issue.

Change-Id: I01c46197dfebb1eb674817ce81792972a06e529f

commit_message:

commit_message:
[rally-jobs] turn off telemetry services by default

Most of our jobs do not require telemetry services, which took time for
installation and even more - can break all rally jobs.

This patch turns off all telemetry services in all jobs. We will return it
someday to test ceilometer scenarios, but such changes requires a lot of LOC
and we need to unblock gates asap.

Change-Id: Ie4b9c641c58715a1f8af379d01c2006b34c953f7

subject: Have run-tox-with-oslo-master not upgrade to many things
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-11-17 20:18:16.000000000', 'files': ['jenkins/scripts/run-tox-with-oslo-master.sh'], 'message': 'Have run-tox-with-oslo-master not upgrade to many things

Instead of having the script that gets ran invalidating the
upper constraints, which is currently causing requests to get
upgraded to a newer version that is busting nova (and possible
glance) periodic jobs just respect the constraints (and remove
the oslo libraries from those constraints) and do not try to
run pip with -U so that more than desired gets upgraded.

This seems to localize the packages that get installed and upgraded
to a smaller set (hopefully causing less package variance issues).

Change-Id: Ice723851e5c8861cc1db0dfee2ea665e8727a8a4
'}]
commit_message:
Have run-tox-with-oslo-master not upgrade to many things

Instead of having the script that gets ran invalidating the
upper constraints, which is currently causing requests to get
upgraded to a newer version that is busting nova (and possible
glance) periodic jobs just respect the constraints (and remove
the oslo libraries from those constraints) and do not try to
run pip with -U so that more than desired gets upgraded.

This seems to localize the packages that get installed and upgraded
to a smaller set (hopefully causing less package variance issues).

Change-Id: Ice723851e5c8861cc1db0dfee2ea665e8727a8a4

commit_message:
Use dynamic includes for speedup

Now that Ansible 2.x allows for dynamic includes, we can drive a hard
split between the RHEL 6 and RHEL 7 STIG work. This speeds up gate jobs
and avoids situations where a variable is defined in one STIG playbook
versus another.

Implements: blueprint security-rhel7-stig

commit_message:
ProvisionRequest does not distinguish event source

This patchset is to support review
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/396467/ of networking_powervm
patchset. ProvisionRequest in networking_powervm is built on
event generated by nova_powervm when a vif is plugged or unplugged.
It needs a way to identify source of such an event. This patchset
provides it. When a plug or unplug event is generated, corresponding
vif_type is also passed into it under details attribute.

Change-Id: I6266ad485b10bdfa21a7b4e66600dfbd6ab1f2fc
Closes-Bug: #1640564

subject: Add IPManager class for handling IP addresses
revisions:
[{'number': 8, 'created': '2016-11-18 22:07:15.000000000', 'files': ['lib/ip.py', 'tests/test_ip.py', 'tox.ini'], 'message': "Add IPManager class for handling IP addresses

This patch begins work on an 'IPManager' class that further decouples
IP/CIDR manipulation from the openstack-ansible configuration handling
logic.

With this patchset, a new implementation is provided and tested in
isolation, with integration into and replacement of existing code set
for follow up patchsets.

The aim is also to provide a working implementation based on a proposed
IP management API for use with plugins. The proposed API is provided as
the IPBasePlugin class, and generic expectations of the API are
documented there.

A few notable changes exist in the new IPManager class versus the
existing codebase:

    - The Queue.Queue class is not used, but rather a plain, randomized
    list. Reviewing the existing implementation, there does not appear
    to be a need to use the specialized queue class.

    - USED_IPS is moved into a set associated with a given IPManager
    object. The expectation is that dynamic_inventory.py will treat
    IPManager as a singleton, but this implementation allows for
    replacing that singleton in test cases, or using multiple instances
    in some other context.

While the lib/ip.py file is not intended to be executed, the python
shebang line was provided in order to comply with our tox linting
searches.

Change-Id: I06729ac2bc1688a39255f2c8ea0d14131b5c2560
"}]
commit_message:
Add IPManager class for handling IP addresses

This patch begins work on an 'IPManager' class that further decouples
IP/CIDR manipulation from the openstack-ansible configuration handling
logic.

With this patchset, a new implementation is provided and tested in
isolation, with integration into and replacement of existing code set
for follow up patchsets.

The aim is also to provide a working implementation based on a proposed
IP management API for use with plugins. The proposed API is provided as
the IPBasePlugin class, and generic expectations of the API are
documented there.

A few notable changes exist in the new IPManager class versus the
existing codebase:

    - The Queue.Queue class is not used, but rather a plain, randomized
    list. Reviewing the existing implementation, there does not appear
    to be a need to use the specialized queue class.

    - USED_IPS is moved into a set associated with a given IPManager
    object. The expectation is that dynamic_inventory.py will treat
    IPManager as a singleton, but this implementation allows for
    replacing that singleton in test cases, or using multiple instances
    in some other context.

While the lib/ip.py file is not intended to be executed, the python
shebang line was provided in order to comply with our tox linting
searches.

Change-Id: I06729ac2bc1688a39255f2c8ea0d14131b5c2560

Move list_hosts to resource_setup in test_hosts_negative

In HostsAdminNegativeTestJSON, hosts can be get in resource_setup
to avoid getting them repeatedly in each testcase.
Besides, when a nonexistent hostname is needed, we can use the
string 'nonexistent_hostname' directly instead of creating a
random host name. Thus the whole code will look clearer.

subject: Consolidate tox run output into one report
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2016-11-18 22:08:24.000000000', 'files': ['tox.ini'], 'message': "Consolidate tox run output into one report

The original implementation of erasing the coverage data file between
each test was the most accurate method, providing coverage stats in a
'cleanroom' setup, but resulted in extra reports being output. This
doesn't scale very well as more test files are added to the repository.

This patchset removes the extranenous erase command, and adds the `-a`
argument to the run commands, which allows coverage to accumulate data
across runs. Without the `-a` run, the coverage reports for each target
file are cross-contaminated, resulting in different coverage numbers.

Depends-On: I06729ac2bc1688a39255f2c8ea0d14131b5c2560

Change-Id: I4d52f7363e00bba62ed878fe8fa6e593eb21fdde
"}]
commit_message:
Consolidate tox run output into one report

The original implementation of erasing the coverage data file between
each test was the most accurate method, providing coverage stats in a
'cleanroom' setup, but resulted in extra reports being output. This
doesn't scale very well as more test files are added to the repository.

This patchset removes the extranenous erase command, and adds the `-a`
argument to the run commands, which allows coverage to accumulate data
across runs. Without the `-a` run, the coverage reports for each target
file are cross-contaminated, resulting in different coverage numbers.

Depends-On: I06729ac2bc1688a39255f2c8ea0d14131b5c2560

Change-Id: I4d52f7363e00bba62ed878fe8fa6e593eb21fdde

The libvirt driver currently does not set the machine type for a KVM
guest by default.  When not specified, libvirt will use the newest
one it knows about.  Unfortunately, that can result in live
migrations failing if your environment is using different versions of

commit_message:
Expose libvirt/hw_machine_type for consistent machine types.

The libvirt driver currently does not set the machine type for a KVM
guest by default.  When not specified, libvirt will use the newest
one it knows about.  Unfortunately, that can result in live
migrations failing if your environment is using different versions of
the host OS on compute nodes as the destination node may not be able
to support the machine type used when the VM was originally started.

Change-Id: I269ade8997389fc56ce3009fbd0660d1a47a0c4a

commit_message:
Manage enforce_password_check

By setting ENFORCE_PASSWORD_CHECK to `True`, it displays an 'Admin
Password' field on the Change Password form to verify that it is indeed
the admin logged-in who wants to change the password.

Change-Id: If7af97df7a011569a7e14fbab4f880688d7b82c3
Related-Bug: #1640806

commit_message:
Force domain_password parameter to be defined

Having a default value for a password is not acceptable for security
purpose.  We should unset the default value so we make sure catalog fail
if no value is set.  It enforces our users to set a value and stop
opening a security problem.

Change-Id: I41b974f6ece39743bfc2ad922b2f0dad20aec469

commit_message:
Add support for BIOS local boot for GPT label

Ironic doesn't support local booting of images in BIOS boot mode
when the disk_label is GPT. The current changes creates BIOS Boot
partition when the disk_label is chosen as gpt. The partition size
is a configurable parameter.

Change-Id: Iade60da0316b8f1c0bf8ce4c79931c1105d19cec
Closes-bug: #1563291
(cherry picked from commit c6d4f0f463974a3a88eadb22c175c796556cc755)

subject: devstack: Stop setting route pointing back to tenant router
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-11-18 21:28:37.000000000', 'files': ['devstack/entry_points'], 'message': 'devstack: Stop setting route pointing back to tenant router

The is the networking-odl counter part of devstack patch.
change set of df5e69114fa2af663c50e734b4a842c727e6a7e9
change id of If45e3fc15c050cfbac11b57c1eaf137dd7ed816f
This patch removes both IPv4/IPv6 routes for tenant router
unlike the patch of devstack.

> Stop setting route pointing back to tenant router
>
> This removes the logic to add a route pointing to the IPv4
> tenant private network range since the router is performing
> SNAT. If reaching the IPs via the route worked at all, it was
> by accident since this behavior is certainly not guaranteed
> by Neutron.

Change-Id: Ib4c8b0e1737ce6b2e328dd76b432ac137e1173aa
'}]
commit_message:
devstack: Stop setting route pointing back to tenant router

The is the networking-odl counter part of devstack patch.
change set of df5e69114fa2af663c50e734b4a842c727e6a7e9
change id of If45e3fc15c050cfbac11b57c1eaf137dd7ed816f
This patch removes both IPv4/IPv6 routes for tenant router
unlike the patch of devstack.

> Stop setting route pointing back to tenant router
>
> This removes the logic to add a route pointing to the IPv4
> tenant private network range since the router is performing
> SNAT. If reaching the IPs via the route worked at all, it was
> by accident since this behavior is certainly not guaranteed
> by Neutron.

Change-Id: Ib4c8b0e1737ce6b2e328dd76b432ac137e1173aa

Replace deprecated LOG.warn with LOG.warning

LOG.warn is deprecated in Python 3 [1].
This change switches it to the non-deprecated LOG.warning

[1]https://docs.python.org/3/library/logging.html#logging.warning

Closes-Bug: #1508442

commit_message:
Some classes not define __ne__() built-in function

Some classes defines __eq__() built-in function, but does
not define __ne__() built-in function, so self.assertEqual works
but self.assertNotEqual does not work at all in this test case in
python2. This patch will fix it.

Change-Id: Ia5789c773959e75e8c1c99d82129cac1df30cc64
Closes-Bug: #1586268

commit_message:
Add QoS bandwidth limit for instance ingress traffic

This patch introduces the new parameter "direction" to
the QoS bandwidth limit rule. It will allow the creation
of bandwidth limit rules for either ingress or egress
traffic. For backwards compatibility the default direction
will be egress.

DocImpact: Ingress bandwidth limit available for QoS
APIImpact: New type of parameter for QoS rule in neutron API

Change-Id: Iab86c77366bb3290c17f58f6a5a2a206414e49b6
Partial-Bug: #1560961

Currently the exists method in IpNetnsCommand class of the ip_lib
module determines whether the namespace 'exists' or not with the
output of the command: ip -o netns list.

As reported in the bug, there may be cases where there may be an
empty namespace file in /run/netns but the namespace may not
actually exist. In such cases the dhcp agent throws an error
which isn't currently handled. It may also result in many tap

This patch fixes the above bug by modifying the exist method
to additionally execute a command in the namespace:
ip netns exec <namespace> ip addr, in order to confirm that the

This handles the error thrown by add_device_to_namespace method

commit_message:
neutron-dhcp-agent generates thousands of interfaces on a failure

Currently the exists method in IpNetnsCommand class of the ip_lib
module determines whether the namespace 'exists' or not with the
output of the command: ip -o netns list.

As reported in the bug, there may be cases where there may be an
empty namespace file in /run/netns but the namespace may not
actually exist. In such cases the dhcp agent throws an error
which isn't currently handled. It may also result in many tap
interfaces getting generated.

This patch fixes the above bug by modifying the exist method
to additionally execute a command in the namespace:
ip netns exec <namespace> ip addr, in order to confirm that the
namespace does actually exist.

This handles the error thrown by add_device_to_namespace method
resulting from non-existent namespaces and also stops generating
lots of tap interfaces.

Change-Id: I2015deb8dcd2b69755ac283e328ad1e6946311fe
Closes-Bug: #1561695

commit_message:
Spawn metadata proxy for DVR+HA routers

If we run L3 agent as dvr_snat mode in all nodes (include network
and compute nodes), when creating an ha + distributed router, L3 agent
will destroy metadata proxy in all backup nodes, this cause instances
in that nodes can't fetch metadata info via metadata proxy in router
namespace.

This patch permits standby dvr+ha routers to spawn metadata proxy.

Co-Authored-By: Dongcan Ye <hellochosen@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1606741
Change-Id: I7350a991d2f2e778305d49483bcc82a8cf758d3a

commit_message:
Moving query builder methods to Subnet OVO

This patchset isolates model interrelationship under neutron/objects.
Query includes Subnet, SubnetServiceType and SegmentHostMapping models.
Since Subnet is of more relevance, query builder methods are being
moved to neutron/objects/subnet.py.

commit_message:
No more implicit conversion to unicode/str

From the oslo.log usage, error should be converted to unicode either
by calling six.text_type() or by using a unicode formatting string to
provide contex.[1]

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.log/usage.html#
    no-more-implicit-conversion-to-unicode-str
Closes-Bug: #1529534

Change-Id: Ifd9a69501534a691b56a6e30024382296e2f03aa
